      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p><strong>Key observation:</strong> Micron suffered heavily in 2023 with negative margins across the board during a memory glut. By 2025, operating margins fully recovered to 26%, but FCF margin remains squeezed by massive capex required to tool fabs for next-generation nodes.</p>

  <!-- ═══ SENSITIVITY ANALYSIS ═══ -->
  <h2>Sensitivity Analysis</h2>
  <p>Our base case uses 18% growth and an 11% discount rate. Given Micron's cyclicality, a slight misjudgment in the cycle peak heavily skews intrinsic value. Find the combination you believe in.</p>

  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table class="sensitivity-table">
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Discount Rate ↓ / Growth →</th>
          {sensitivityGrowth.map(g => (
            <th class={g === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>{(g * 100)}%</th>
          ))}
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        {sensitivityTable.map(row => (
          <tr>
            <td>{(row.dr * 100)}%</td>
            {row.values.map((v, i) => (
              <td class={row.dr === discountRate && sensitivityGrowth[i] === growthRatePhase1 ? 'current' : ''}>
                ${v}
              </td>
            ))}
          </tr>
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>
  <p>The highlighted cell is our base case. Notice how wide the outcomes are depending on growth projections. At $465/share, the market expects exceptional performance indefinitely.</p>

  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses — and how it might bias our estimate.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>HBM dominance:</strong> High Bandwidth Memory is heavily supply-constrained and enjoys phenomenal pricing power due to AI server demand. If Micron can capture sustained outsized margin share here, our 18% growth could be severely understated.</li>
    <li><strong>Geopolitics:</strong> Domestic fab subsidies (CHIPS Act) could structurally lower future capex burdens, allowing higher FCF conversion in outer years.</li>
    <li><strong>End of cycle volatility:</strong> If the memory industry has structurally consolidated into an oligopoly that finally exerts pricing discipline, the "bust" years may never be as bad as 2023 again.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>AI hardware bubble popping:</strong> If hyper-scalers pull back on GPU purchases, HBM demand will evaporate, causing a devastating cyclical collapse. Our model linearly projects growth.</li>
    <li><strong>Capex arms race:</strong> Samsung and SK Hynix are aggressive competitors. Micron might be forced to permanently elevate capital expenditures just to maintain market share, forever compressing FCF.</li>
    <li><strong>China restrictions:</strong> Losing revenue access to China or facing subsidized Chinese state-backed memory fab dumping could crush margins.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a DCF for a highly cyclical stock like Micron?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">It is uniquely challenging to DCF cyclical companies because their terminal value heavily depends on whether year 5 is a peak or a trough. However, a DCF still forces you to map out your assumptions about the cycle's peak and what cash flows look like. It provides better context than trying to value MU based on a P/E multiple at the top of a cycle.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why 11% discount rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Micron is riskier than a SaaS company or consumer defensive. A beta of ~1.2 combined with a high capital intensity justifies a required return closer to 11%.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why 18% FCF growth from FY2025?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">While FCF was $1.66B in FY2025, it was heavily weighed down by capex. As the company realizes pricing power from HBM arrays tied to AI deployments, operating cash flow should significantly outpace capex growth, creating high operating leverage. 18% assumes strong follow-through on AI promises over the next 5 years.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, tax situation, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

